  "assistantText": "Your counter circuit is ready! 🎉 Here's the full breakdown:\n\n---\n\n## 🔌 Wiring Table\n\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Pin | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| D2 | R_A → Display | a | Segment A |\n| D3 | R_B → Display | b | Segment B |\n| D4 | R_C → Display | c | Segment C |\n| D5 | R_D → Display | d | Segment D |\n| D6 | R_E → Display | e | Segment E |\n| D7 | R_F → Display | f | Segment F |\n| D8 | R_G → Display | g | Segment G |\n| D9 | Button | a | Active LOW via INPUT_PULLUP |\n| GND | Display | gnd | Common Cathode |\n| GND | Button | b | Button return |\n\nAll 7 segment resistors (220Ω each) are wired **in-series** between the Arduino pins and the display — no extra breadboard rows needed.\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 How It Works\n\n- **Button on D9** uses the Arduino's internal pull-up resistor — no external resistor needed.\n- Each **button press** (HIGH→LOW edge) increments the counter.\n- After **9**, it wraps back to **0**.\n- The `lastBtnState` variable ensures it counts **once per press**, not once per loop tick (debounce via edge detection).\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ Power Budget Summary\n\n| Item | Current Draw |\n|---|---|\n| Each lit segment | ~(5V − 2V) / 220Ω ≈ **13.6 mA** |\n| Max segments lit (digit 8) | 7 × 13.6 ≈ **95 mA** — but shared via 1 common cathode pin |\n| Per Arduino output pin | ≤ 13.6 mA ✅ (well under 20 mA limit) |\n| Button pin | ~0 mA (INPUT_PULLUP, digital read only) ✅ |\n| Total board draw | ~40–95 mA depending on digit — within Uno's USB 500 mA limit ✅ |\n\nAll per-pin currents are **safe** at ≤ 13.6 mA each. 🟢",
